There are some pretty good write-ups on how they made some of the early games from discrete logic

One of my other dreams is to restore a rackmount PDP-11. The cards on them are extremely simple. The last generation of PDP-11 overlapped the 80s IBM-PC, and the PDP cards even then were rudimentary compared to the average PC card; people bench repaired those old PC cards like it was nothing.
In a strange way, the older the machine is the more it's like a classic car. You're not always rebuilding to be a daily driver, but for the thrill of the engineering that went into it.

I've never been big on HAM, but some of those old tube stereo amps are utterly beautiful.

I'm going to see if I have fresh strings for my Strat, and if I do, I'll be in my bunk..

>an unusually long amount of time researching miniscule details
No such thing, depending upon how you look at it. Now that you have the knowledge, you can do Things with it. In another story. Turn it (or some tangental aspect of it) into a Chekhov's Gun. Do further research so you don't Dunning-Kruger yourself because you THOUGHT you understood what 20 minutes of reading meant. I lack context here of what you were attempting or what you learned, but it's REAL easy to stop too soon on something because you think "Oh shit yeah I'm a PhD on this now." And, turns out, you're not.

Anyway, 20 minutes may not be enough time, but it certainly isn't wasted time. You'll get to use it one way or another. That's what being a writer means: you slowly become a library of useless knowledge to tuck into all your work over the years.

Don't forget to make new experiences. Different exercise than book knowledge from a Wikipedia page.

Not long ago I ran across an "Internet manual" for home-made napalm. Had I tried to write about that based upon my reading it would have been a fiasco. But, I actually made some and played with it. Took a good bit of experimentation with materials and proportions before I got it right. Scary shit, and I can now write about its texture, smell, ignition, burn time, damage, etc. like I've never seen anyone else ever write about it.

Uh, yeah ... that's about ten lost days. Worth it.
